I know using the words “good” and “bad” for parents can be unfair and I want to explain why I used them here.

There is a particularly difficult dynamic that can happen between emotionally immature parents and their adult children. In this dynamic, the parent struggles with admitting their faults, areas of weakness, or areas where improvement was needed. It feels like addressing any of these things will = I’M A BAD PARENT. In an attempt to avoid feeling bad, the parent will label the child bad. Because if you were a bad kid, everything I did was justified and I have no responsibility. Instead of an honest conversation and repair, it becomes ME vs. YOU. The good parent vs. the bad kid.

Your mistakes as a parent don’t define you. Your ability to listen, understand, and repair with your adult child is what makes you a good parent.

No child is responsible for their parent’s parenting decisions. You weren’t a bad kid.

Some excerpts from my latest free email, “Are Some Adult Children Just Toxic?”

I can’t tell you how many DM’s I have asking me some variation of this question. I know this is a very difficult, nuanced topic and I tried my best to tackle it.

I share a lot about the adult child + parent dynamic on social media.

I usually hear from these two groups when I post:
1. Parents who feel they have been 100% falsely accused and they have nothing to discuss or remedy with their adult child.
2. Adult children who absolutely experienced abuse at the hands of their parent(s) and have every right to cut these people out of their life, especially if they have no intention of apologizing or changing.

I think we are missing a huge group of people in the middle.

Based on my experience as a therapist, I know with 100% certainty that there are adult children who do treat their parents poorly, there are abusive/defensive parents that won’t change, and there are parents who want to learn if they’re being harmful to their adult children. If you were abused by your parents and feel secure in your desire to cut them off or protect yourself from further abuse, I stand with you. I also think if you fall into this group, this might not be the email for you.

If you don’t fall into that group, you might be:
- An adult child who recognizes they haven’t always treated their parent with kindness or respect.
- A parent who wants to evaluate if they are being toxic or abusive towards their adult child.
- A parent or adult child who wants to understand how a unique interplay of nature and nurture led to this outcome.

I posted about this a few days ago on my feed (it’s a text post, white with Twitter format) and there are over 450 comments there discussing this if you’d like to hear some other perspectives.

As I continue to investigate and talk about the divide between adult children and their parents, I hear a few recurring themes from parents of adults. A lot of these themes are positioned as absolute truths and there’s little investigation into how they happened.

We cannot expect adult children to behave in a way that was never modeled for them or taught. Kids are not born knowing how to show empathy or gratitude. They don’t know how to communicate or problem solve. These things have to be taught and modeled.

So when I hear beliefs about adult children from parents like ‘“they’re just spoiled,” “they’re ungrateful,” “they have no empathy,” or “they have no idea how to forgive,” I’m wondering: how did this happen? What are some potential reasons why your adult child is behaving this way?

Yes, personality + other external influences impact how an adult child behaves. It’s not just the family. But I worry about what happens when we saddle young adults with fixed descriptions like “spoiled” without ever investigating why they seem this way to their parents.

Adult children do not turn 18 and become “entitled,” “spoiled,” “selfish,” etc.

Did something happen in your family system or in their life along the way to lead to this outcome?
How did you and other influences in their life model and discuss these behaviors?
How do you model forgiveness and empathy?
How do you show gratitude as a family?

Sometimes we call people things like “spoiled” or “entitled,” instead of stating our own needs. If you feel this way about your adult child, is there something you feel you’re missing? What is it that you need?

It’s never too late to have a positive influence.

Estrangement is an ambiguous loss.

Ambiguous loss is a term pioneered by Pauline Boss, PhD and she defines it as “a relational disorder caused by the lack of facts surrounding the loss of a loved one.” Ambiguous loss is different because there is no verification of death and no promise that the person will come back or be the way they used to be. With ambiguous loss, the person may be deceased, living, or missing.

Whenever you’re setting a boundary, I want you to think about “what am I going to do?” I want you to try to stop focusing on “what am I going to get them to do with my boundary”

I’ll give you an example. Toddlers will hit sometimes. They think it’s funny, they’re learning cause and effect, they’re frustrated, etc. If we tell the toddler “don’t hit,” we may not get the result we want because we cannot control the toddler’s behavior and they often don’t have the skills to manage their behavior in that moment either. They will often keep hitting and we will escalate in our attempt to get them to stop. Our behavior doesn’t help the problem and usually just makes it way worse.

Instead we can say, “if you’re going to keep hitting me, I’m going to put you down and move away.” If they’re old enough to understand, we can explain why we don’t want to be hit, why we can’t hit, and what they can do with their hands instead.

We often set boundaries with adults in the same way. We keep putting ourselves in situations where we can get hurt and scream “stop hurting me!”

When thinking about boundaries with family, I want you to start with what you can do differently and less about how you can change them.

Was your childhood better than your parents’? In what ways are you trying to make your child’s life better than yours was?

I know it would be nice for you child to realize “how good they have it,” but they just don’t have the perspective. You also don’t know what it’s like to be a chilwill know struggles that your child can’t even imagine. Your child will experience childhood in a way that you can’t fully understand simply because the would they’re growing up in is different. When they’re older maybe they’ll be able to hear stories and understand, but they still won’t have lived it.

We make the lives of our children better because we love them, we want better for them, we know better, and because we can. Not because we want our children to give us an award for our efforts.

Dismantle the generational trauma. Do better. Learn more. Break cycles. And listen to the ways your kids are struggling even if that struggle is different from yours.

a theme I notice in therapy: 

people with a “be strong” response to distress (doing everything, not sharing, pretending not to be bothered) can become resentful of those who show their emotions and ask for help.

If you respond to hardship by turning inward and outwardly displaying intense strength, you may feel desperate for someone to notice and take care of you.

If you respond to hardship by being “the tough one,” you may think people who show their emotions and ask for help are “too emotional” or “too dramatic.”

This behavior is often dictated by an inner core belief about what it means to be strong.
“Strength means I can do it by myself.”
“Weakness means I need help.”
“I can’t do this and I need someone to save me.”

If you’re holding it all in and doing everything yourself, you may look down on others who are getting help/support. Looking at them as dramatic, needy, etc. helps you reaffirm your “strong” position and avoid the painful feeling of being alone and/or feeling misunderstood.

Being tough is great. But rejecting help + keeping everything inside isn’t strength. Sometimes it’s just a mask because it feels better to say “I don’t need anyone,” than to say “I’m afraid of letting someone in because they might let me down, so I just do it all myself.”

Everyone deserves support when they’re struggling - even the “strong” ones. Real strength includes knowing you have the capacity to help yourself and you will benefit from outside support.

Has this been your experience?

Sometimes the mother wound is caused by an abusive mother with ill-intentions who intentionally manipulates and withholds love, affection and protection from her child. And, many of you who are healing from the mother wound had mothers who were unsupported, traumatized, trapped in oppressive systems, and/or who were wounded by their own mothers.

This doesn’t change the pain that you feel, but it does change how you come to understand and relate to your mother. You may set the same boundaries or make the same changes in your relationship with your mother, but the story you tell yourself will be wildly different.

I believe there is a difference between how each of these mother wounds feels and in how you will approach healing from them:
1. My mother did not love me. She intentionally hurt me and wanted me to suffer.
2. My mother did not know how to love me or herself. She was suffering from her own mother wound and harmed me regularly. She is unwilling to look at the ways she harmed me and learn a new way.
3. My mother did not know how to love me or herself. She was suffering from her own mother wound and harmed me regularly. She is willing to look at the ways she harmed me and learn a new way.

Your mother holds immense power over the narrative of your life. She was probably your first experience with acceptance + rejection, love + hate, or attention + neglect. Her actions influenced how you see the world and yourself before you were even a living, breathing human being.

But your mother is not an island and she is not the only potential source of your pain. She is also a human who has been deeply impacted by the world that she grew up in. She has her own wounds that she either didn’t have the resources to heal, denied, or refused to heal. Maybe you’re one of the lucky ones with a mother who has decided to work on understanding how her own upbringing and wounding has impacted her mothering.

Rachel grew up in a home with a lot of violence and emotional abandonment. Her father did everything in excess: he drank a lot, yelled a lot, and disappeared a lot.

She remembers feeling desperate for his attention, waiting up at night and hoping she'd hear him come through the door. But every time he did come home, things were miserable. He would yell and throw things. Her mom would cry and beg him to stop while Rachel hid in her room.

Rachel missed something she had never experienced and would search for it for the rest of her life.
I've met many women like Rachel. Women whose fathers never offered them nurturance, security, or love. When women like Rachel struggle to form romantic attachments in adulthood, it's easy to assume they lack a solid relationship with their father. It's an old cliche, but is there truth to it?

It seems like Rachel's story fits in perfectly with some of these theories, but it would be incorrect to assume that the sole reason Rachel is struggling is because of her relationship with her father. The theories I listed above are just theories. Theories and data are essential, but how we apply them to our lives is even more critical.

I want you to feel empowered by how you view your life. If the lens of "my dad wasn't around, and this is why I struggle" is helpful and empowering for you, use it. If you're struggling in your romantic relationships and you're not sure it's because of your relationship with your father, it might not be.

We cannot assume that every woman who struggles with romantic partnerships has "daddy issues." And many women go on to have healthy partnerships despite having a complicated relationship with their fathers.

If you are a daughter who was negatively impacted by the relationship with your father, it's not your fault. It makes sense why you seek out the familiar. You can create new, healthy relationships in your life.

This is the core of the @callinghome.co approach: acceptance. It doesn’t matter what topic we’re discussing, this is the foundation of the discussion.

I want to help you stop fighting against who this person is. I want to help you accept who they continue to be.

This doesn’t mean you like how they behave or you allow them to treat you badly. It just means you accept this is how they are right now and you need to learn how to have a relationship with this version of them, or not.

Instead of changing them, you could work on improving yourself. You’d be ready for a relationship in the future if they change. 

Acceptance will finally give you peace. I promise it helps.

When it comes to our families, we really only know what we know, until we are exposed to something else. And as children, we have no choice but to live in the environment we're born into.

As adults, we have choices, but we're often so used to playing our unique role in the family and the risk of isolation keeps people trapped in unhealthy dynamics.

Unhealthy, dysfunctional family systems are detrimental to our health and the earlier/longer someone is exposed, the more likely it is that they will be negatively impacted. Being around people who are constantly critical, abusive, and hurtful is literally bad for your health.

- UCLA: "Risky families are characterized by conflict and aggression and by relationships that are cold, unsupportive, and neglectful. These family characteristics create vulnerabilities and/or interact with genetically based vulnerabilities in offspring that produce disruptions in psychosocial functioning (specifically
emotion processing and social competence), disruptions in stress-responsive biological regulatory systems, including sympathetic-adrenomedullary and hypothalamic-pituitary–adrenocortical functioning,
and poor health behaviors, especially substance abuse"

- APA: "Families with frequent conflict (e.g., repeated episodes of anger, aggression, and yelling) 
and cold and neglectful relationships (e.g., absence of parental emotional support and 
unavailability) can be especially damaging to a child's physical health The Risky Families model described by Repetti et al. (2002) proposes that these family characteristics can create vulnerabilities for children that have the potential to disrupt multiple biological systems and put children at risk for future chronic health problems."

- Segrin, C., & Flora, J. (2017): "In the past 20 years scientists have made astonishing discoveries of possible psychophysiological mechanisms linking marital and family conflict with poor physical health outcomes."

With all this information, you have to ask yourself: How long will I be able to pretend this isn't having an impact on my mood, relationships, sleep, or work?
